Clear answer:

describe_iam_instance_profile_associations gives:

IamInstanceProfile.Arn ← already in describe_instances
IamInstanceProfile.Id ← already in describe_instances
State: "associated" ← not needed for attack paths
AssociationId ← not needed
Its own UID is iip-assoc-XXXXX (not the instance ARN) — causes a separate asset to be created
Verdict: disable it. describe_instances already has everything needed for attack paths. Keeping describe_iam_instance_profile_associations creates a separate iam_instance_profile_association asset with a different UID — adding noise, no value.

The same logic applies generally: if a dependent/independent operation emits data already covered by another independent operation, disable it.

