Read threat_analyzer.py (lines 1056-1135)
Now I understand the full picture. The threat engine reads from inventory_findings but only reads specific columns (configuration, resource_uid, resource_type, etc.) — it does NOT read properties.

The relationship builder in the inventory engine runs IN MEMORY during the scan and builds relationships from asset.metadata["emitted_fields"]. Those relationships go into inventory_relationships. The threat engine/graph builder reads inventory_relationships for graph traversal.

So the actual flow for attack paths is:

Inventory engine scans → builds assets with emitted_fields in memory

RelationshipBuilder extracts references like IamInstanceProfile.Arn from emitted_fields to create EC2→IAM relationships

Relationships get written to inventory_relationships

Threat engine reads inventory_relationships to build the attack graph

The key question is whether IamInstanceProfile is actually in emitted_fields at scan time — if it is, the RelationshipBuilder will pick it up and create the relationship; if not, the connection won't exist for the threat engine to traverse.

When normalize_from_discovery processes describe_instances records, it merges the stored emitted_fields from the database with the raw_response data. For EC2 instances, the emitted_fields should contain individual instance properties including IamInstanceProfile. But I need to check what write_asset_index actually stores in emitted_fields — that's where the disconnect might be.

Looking at how the asset data flows through the next scan: when _load_previous_scan reconstructs assets from the inventory, it reads the properties column and merges it into the asset's metadata. So if emitted_fields was stored in properties, it should be available as metadata["emitted_fields"] during the next run.

